04676nam a22007215i 9780813562094DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2013005971  a97808135620947 a10.36019/97808135620942doi  a(DE-B1597)528968  a(OCoLC)863158192  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN1995.9.S74bC66 2014 4aPN1995.9S74bC66 2013eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a791.43/62223  aAP 332832rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7300:7431 aCoon, David R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLook Closer :bSuburban Narratives and American Values in Film and Television /cDavid R. Coon. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b17 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Welcome to the Neighborhood -- t1. Traditional Values: Nostalgia and Self-Reflexivity in Visual Representations of Suburbia -- t2. Back Yard Fences: The Public, the Private, and the Family in Suburban Dramas -- t3. Suburban Citizenship: Defining Community through the Exclusion of Racial and Sexual Minorities -- t4. Desperate Husbands: The Crisis of Hegemonic Masculinity in Post-9/11 Suburbia -- t5. Protecting the Suburban Lifestyle: Consumption, Crime, and the American Dream -- tConclusion: There Goes the Neighborhood -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years, the media landscape in the United States has followed a pattern similar to that of the physical landscape by becoming increasingly suburbanized. Although it is a far cry from reality, the fantasy of a perfect suburban life still exists in the collective imagination of millions of Americans. This dream of suburban perfection is built around a variety of such ideologically conservative values and ideals as the importance of tradition, the centrality of the nuclear family, the desire for a community of like-minded neighbors, the need for clearly defined gender roles, and the belief that with hard work and determination, anyone can succeed. Building on the relationships between suburban life and American identity, Look Closer examines and interprets recent narratives that challenge the suburban ideal to reveal how directors and producers are mobilizing the spaces of suburbia to tell new kinds of stories about America. David R. Coon argues that the myth of suburban perfection, popularized by postwar sitcoms and advertisements, continues to symbolize a range of intensely debated issues related to tradition, family, gender, race, and citizenship. Through close examinations of such films as American Beauty, The Truman Show, and Mr. & Mrs. Smith as well as such television series as Desperate Housewives, Weeds, and Big Love, the book demonstrates how suburbia is used to critique the ideologies that underpin the suburban American Dream.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSuburban life in motion pictures. 0aSuburban life on television. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356209440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813562094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813562094.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK